===Noun phrase===
{{wikipediapar|peremptory norm}}
'''jus cogens'''
#{{law}} a [[constraining]] [[law]] or [[peremptory]] [[norm]]; a [[fundamental]] [[principle]] of [[international law]] considered to be accepted by all states.

The Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties, 1969, defines the effect of jus cogens norms on conflicting treaty rules in Article 53 as follows:

"A treaty is void if, at the time of its conclusion, it conflicts with a peremptory norm of general international law. For the purposes of the present Convention, a peremptory norm of general  international law is a norm accepted and recognized by the international community of States as a
whole as a norm from which no derogation is permitted and which can be modified only by a subsequent norm of general international law having the same character."

In other words, it would be contrary for two or more States to enter into a treaty in order to commit genocide, aggression, slavery, racial discrimination or other acts contrary to the basic rules of the international legal order.  Such treaty rules would be of no force or effect because they run counter to the peremptory, i.e. compelling law, of the international legal system.  In such case, States could not defend their action on the basis that they were under an international treaty obligation to perform the act, because such act would be invalid from the start.  In this sense, the concept of jus cogens, which comes originally from ancient Roman Law, approximates the rule in domestic law, that contracts to perform illegal acts (for example, to buy and sell illegal narcotic drugs, or to order an assassination) are themselves illegal and of no legal force or effect.


See further Chapter IV of the Emerging System of International Criminal Law: Developments in Codification and Implementation (1997) [[Lyal Sunga | Lyal S. Sunga]] on "Advent of Normative Hierarchy in International Law   and its Relation to Individual Criminal Responsibility" pages 229-248, discussing the relation among jus cogens, obligations erga omnes and 'international crimes of State' as well as the relation of these concepts to normative hierarchy in international law and individual criminal responsibility.